In flanker paradigms, interference effects are typically inferred from prolonged RT or decreased accuracy (Accy) rates for central target stimuli with incongruent (as compared with congruent) flanker stimuli, with smaller increases of RT and smaller decreases of Accy rates, respectively, suggesting better interference resolution (and, hence, higher efficiency of ECF). Accordingly, we computed the Accy of indicating the correct direction of the central stimuli, and measured the reaction times (RT) of valid responses. The relative increase in average RT for incongruent as compared to congruent stimuli was calculated, using the following established9 Equation (4)4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
